LAGOS  – The Nigeria Customs Service (NCS), Ports and Terminal Multipurpose Services Limited (PTML), said it generated N224,470,113,733.00 revenue to the Federal Government coffers between January and December, 2021. This represented about 94 percent of the revenue target of N238,224,920,038.88 set for 2020 and adopted by the command in 2021. This also showed a surplus of N35,122,548,242:00, when compared with the total revenue generated in the previous year of 2020, which was N189,347,565,309.00, which represents an increase of 19 percent. APM Terminals Apapa Transforming Into World-Class Facility –… ANLCA Decries FG’s High Revenue Target For Customs, Says It’ll… The Monthly breakdown of the revenue showed that in January 2021, the command generated N15,205,823,545.00 as against N16,456,582,954.22 made in the same period, 2020, with a percentage difference of -7.2, in February 2021, it generated a revenue of N11,706,947, 150: 00; compared to N13,300,872,189.64, with percentage decrease of -11.9%, when compared to the same period in 2020; in March, it netted a revenue of N19,937,869,175:00, indicating 27.4 % increase when compared to N15,646,193,726.04 in the same period last year. In April 2021, it generated a huge revenue of N17,938,794,417:00 with a percentage increase of 59.6, when compared to N11,241,400,911.00 generated the same period last year. In May 2021, the command made another huge revenue of N17,606,073,741:00 representing a percentage increase of 28.9, when compared to the revenue of N13,661,428,914.48 netted the same period in 2020, while in June 2021, the command made N22,253,694,223.00, compared to N17,512,236,904.07 netted in 2020 with 27.1% increase. In July 2021, the command achieved N19,532,512,815.00 revenue representing 33 percent when compared to N14,661,692,533.36 made at the same period in 2020. In August, the command made N21,835,143,596.00 as against N18,147,171,910:00 generated in 2020, an increase of 20 percent. POLL In September 2021, the command netted N19,004,755,983.00, representing 9 percent increase when compared to N17,407,378,070.00 generated in the same month in 2020. In October, 2021, the command made N20,199,846,443.00 an increase of 46 percent when compared to N13,882,652,173:00 netted in October 2020. In November 2021, the command generated N19,936,017,517.00 an increase of 16 percent when compared to N17,242,894,695:00 netted in the same period in 2020, while in December 2021, it generated N19,313,653,128:00 with a minus of -4.3 percent when compared to N20,187,060,328.02 netted in 2020. “Thus, a total sum of N 224,470,113,733.00 was collected into the Federation account between January and December 2021, which is 19 % increase when compared to N 189,347,565,309.00 generated in the same period in 2020. Comptroller Festus Okun, the Customs Area Controller of PTML Command, who revealed all these during a press briefing in Lagos, said that the command sustained and improved on various measures emplaced to enhance facilitation of legitimate trade, adding that some of the measures were in the area of capacity building for officers, strengthening of dispute resolution committee and building a strong team for quality service delivery, thus engendering ease of doing business. Again, NDLEA Intercepts Hard Drugs At Tin Can Sea Port, Others ISO: LADOL Maintains Lead In Compliance, Retains Certification “We have a functional help-desk, while we keep our doors open to stakeholders for direct access,” Comptroller Okun said. In the area of National Security, he said that the command attached so much importance to the national security, adding that officers and men of his command carefully conducted physical examination of cargo to ensure that all importations are done in strict compliance with extant laws, “especially in the area of compliance with regulatory requirements for controlled items and enforcement of import prohibition laws.” Speaking on the inter-agency collaboration and stakeholders’ engagement, the Customs boss said: “It is on record that a very robust relationship exists among the various government agencies operating in the command. “These are agencies like the Nigeria Police, NDLEA, NAFDAC, SON, NESREA. “We have effectively functioned as the lead agency towards ease of doing business in the port. “This has greatly contributed to the efficiency in service delivery.” He said the command had continued to maintain a cordial relationship with the various stakeholders like importers, exporters, licensed customs agents, freight forwarders and others.